==English==

===Etymology===
There are two popular possible etymologies:
*A reference to the fuly formed meticulous battle plans laid by [[W:Bernard Law Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein|Field Marshall Monty]]
*A full three piece suit from Montague Burton founder of [[W:Burton (clothes retailer)|Burton Menswear]].
The etymology was covered by the BBC documentary [[Balderdash]] & [[Piffle]]. There was first hand oral evidence from the 1950s for the Burton theory. Popular enough to be registered as a shop name for a cafe in 1978.

===Noun===
'''[[full]] [[monty]]'''

# (''British slang'') All inclusive; everything; a whole package.
#: ''I thought he was only going to buy the basic kit, but he bought the '''full monty'''''.

